orkshire, England":"Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"about 1168–1206":"circa 1168–1206","1166–Male":"1166–Overleden","1168–1206":"1168–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","1172–Female":"1172–Overleden","1196–1239":"1196–1239","1135–1195":"1135–1195","1206":"1206","1239":"1239","about 1195":"circa 1195","1135":"1135","1168":"1168","1166":"1166","1196":"1196","about 1168":"circa 1168","1195":"1195","1172":"1172","about 1196":"circa 1196","1170":"1170","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1168–1206":"about 1168–1206","1166–Male":"1166–Deceased","1168–1206":"1168–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1172–Female":"1172–Deceased","1196–1239":"1196–1239","1135–1195":"1135–1195","1206":"1206","1239":"1239","about 1195":"about 1195","1135":"1135","1168":"1168","1166":"1166","1196":"1196","about 1168":"about 1168","1195":"1195","1172":"1172","about 1196":"about 1196","1170":"1170","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thornton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places throughout England and Scotland so called, from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The placename is most frequent in northern England, especially Yorkshire, where there are at least 16 possible sources for the surname.","Irish: Anglicized (translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Sceachán</i>’ (see   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thorton","meanings":["(1997: 465;2007: 2025; 2010: NA)","English: probably a shortened form of   Thornton  , or a habitational name from Thorton in Marnhull, Dorset, which has the same origin."]},{"name":"Skehan","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> or <b>Ó Sceacháin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Sceachán</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>sceach</i> ‘briar, thorn bush’. The Gaelic name has sometimes been ‘translated’ as   Thornton  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Roger de Thornton was born about 1168, in Yorkshire, England as the son of Ralph de Thornton. He married Emma about 1195, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1206, at the age of 39."},"et":{"about 1168–1206":"umbes 1168–1206","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1168–1206":"1168–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","1196–1239":"1196–1239","1135–1195":"1135–1195","1206":"1206","1239":"1239","about 1195":"umbes 1195","1135":"1135","1168":"1168","1166":"1166","1196":"1196","about 1168":"umbes 1168","1195":"1195","1172":"1172","about 1196":"umbes 1196","1170":"1170","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1168–1206":"noin 1168–1206","1166–Male":"1166–Kuollut","1168–1206":"1168–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1172–Female":"1172–Kuollut","1196–1239":"1196–1239","1135–1195":"1135–1195","1206":"1206","1239":"1239","about 1195":"noin 1195","1135":"1135","1168":"1168","1166":"1166","1196":"1196","about 1168":"noin 1168","1195":"1195","1172":"1172","about 1196":"noin 1196","1170":"1170","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1168–1206":"environ 1168–1206","1166–Male":"1166–Décédé","1168–1206":"1168–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Décédée","1172–Female":"1172–Décédée","1196–1239":"1196–1239","1135–1195":"1135–1195","1206":"1206","1239":"1239","about 1195":"environ 1195","1135":"1135","1168":"1168","1166":"1166","1196":"1196","about 1168":"environ 1168","1195":"1195","1172":"1172","about 1196":"environ 1196","1170":"1170","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Roger de Thornton est né environ 1168, à Everwyck, Angleterre, fils de Ralph de Thornton. Il a épousé Emma environ 1195, à Everwyck, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1206, à l’âge de 39 ans."},"de":{"about 1168–12